-
My frustration just keeps growing everytime I have to open my images in photoshop to censor the photos I take. Not only it's time consuming (because i want to make it look good) but it just breaks my heart to have to do this. The other day the software was being super slow and it inspired me to create this image.

 A picture is worth a thousand words and this one encapsulates all of my feelings about censorship on this platform.
My latest shoot for Patreon. It was such a joy to work with the sublime and radiant @lydiavictor12 for this. All uncensored series is up now. Link in the bio babe 🐞🍒🍄

CHANGES, ART & FEARS - I've been going through a lot of changes lately, which is why I haven't been super active here. However, I was still creating. And I needed to take my time. 

Thanks to a grant from the @canada.council for a project called "I Once Was Who I Am," I've got a newfound sense of freedom that's inspired me to explore different facets of my creativity.
I've been feeling a bit trapped by exclusively using photography as my medium while having this nagging voice in my head telling me to "stick with what you know," but I knew it was just fear talking. The sense of liberation I experienced during the shooting of "I Once Was Who I Am" pushed me to delve into painting, collaging, and experimenting with various materials to explore some of the themes most important to me: identities, mental health, and the immigrant experience.
In the upcoming weeks, I'll be sharing the portraits I captured for "I Once Was Who I Am," (which was created with the help of my forever partner in art @julie.te ) which I'm really excited about. But I'll also be sharing the diverse work I've been experimenting with.
I'll be honest…I'm a bit anxious about sharing this new work and the explorations. My inner critic keeps telling me, "You're not good enough," "Stick to what you know," "You'll never make it." But recent events have reminded me of life's impermanence and how short our time here is. That was the kick in the butt I needed to go pass some of my fears and just share.
Even though I am feeling a bit lost and in transition. I'm genuinely curious to see where this new creative path takes me. It's all a big question mark. Photography remains a significant part of my creative life, but it's time for me to expand beyond it.
I also just want to have fun with my art and go wherever my heart desires. 
Stay tuned! ✨🫶🏽

‘’lost script’’ - acrylic on c.1960’s rolodex paper cards. 
-
‘’lost script’’ is a deeply personal piece that I created as part of an ongoing research and project, ‘’Can a memory be home’’. It's a testament to my exploration of the relationship between memory and the immigrant experience, as well as a symbol of my quest to bridge my heritage with the memories of my past.

This piece shows the 33 letters of the Neo-Tifinagh alphabet that I wrote with black acrylic paint. These characters are both familiar and foreign to me, a reminder of my birthplace and the culture I left behind. Through this project, I’m embarking on a journey of reconnection, attempting to bridge the gap between my past and my present.

Last summer I found in a thrift store a rolodex that became a canvas for these letters. The rolodex, once a pinnacle of memory systems, has become a relic of the past. It represents not only my capacity to remember and reconnect with my roots but also my own struggle to navigate the complex inner workings of my memories. It’s the fragility and resilience of memory as a mechanism for preserving my past, and, in a broader sense, the immigrant experience itself.

"Lost Script" is a part of my ongoing project, "Can a Memory Be Home" in which I delve into the relationship between memory and the immigrant experience. Using various mediums like paint and archival photographs, I attempt to reconnect with my heritage & the memories that shape my past and present.

In this specific series, I'm teaching myself the Neo-Tifinagh alphabet. By writing sentences on vibrant backgrounds, it creates a powerful mnemonic device while linking me back to my childhood experiences. Painting has always been intertwined with my formative years, making this process a trigger for recalling old memories and a means to learn the alphabet of my birthplace.

I Once Was Who I Am - Julie's portrait 

''Being adopted made my quest for identity a central point in my life.'' -Julie
-
Thanks to the support of the @canada.council, I created "I Once Was Who I Am." In this project, I photographed and interviewed 8 individuals from diverse backgrounds to explore their experiences with the search for identity and its close connection to their mental health. My aim was to initiate a dialogue based on curiosity and compassion.

When I put out an open call for participants on social media, I was overwhelmed by the response, with nearly 100 people reaching out—far more than I had expected. It became evident that this topic resonated deeply with individuals from a wide range of backgrounds.

The inspiration for this project stems from my personal journey as an indigenous immigrant and a queer woman. These are identities that have evolved throughout my life, leading to various challenges with mental health.

Our sense of identity, how we fit into the world around us, profoundly influences and shapes our self-perception. It acts as the lens through which we interpret our experiences. When that sense of self becomes uncertain or our foundation feels unstable, the impact on our mental health can be significant and traumatic.

I am immensely grateful to the 8 courageous individuals who generously shared their time and stories for this project. I am now thrilled and proud to share their portraits and selected interview excerpts. My plan is to transform this into an exhibition, where the full texts will be presented.
